{{italic title}}
'''''A Primate's Memoir''''' is a book by the [[United States|American]] [[biologist]] [[Robert Sapolsky|Robert M. Sapolsky]]. The book documents Sapolsky's years in [[Kenya]] studying [[baboons]] as a graduate student.  The chapters alternate between describing observations of a troop of baboons and the wildly different [[Culture of Africa|culture in Africa]] that he is increasingly cognizant of.  The book portrays an unconventional way of studying [[neurophysiology]] to determine the effects of stress on life expectancy.

The book was nominated for [[The Aventis Prizes for Science Books]] in 2002.

