[[File:IBRA 6.1 Central Ranges.png|thumb|right|The IBRA regions, with Central Ranges in red]] The '''Central Ranges xeric scrub''' is a [[deserts and xeric shrublands]] [[ecoregion]] of [[Australia]].<ref>{{WWF ecoregion|id=aa1302|name=Central Ranges xeric scrub}}</ref>
==Location and description== The region consists of sandy plains with some areas of rocky highland. These plains have a dry climate but do get some rain in both summer and winter. This area contains the remote city of [[Alice Springs, Northern Territory|Alice Springs]] while the grasslands are home to a number of [[Indigenous Australian]] communities or are used for cattle grazing.
==Flora== This ecoregion contains four [[Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia]] (IBRA) bioregions; [[Burt Plain]], [[MacDonnell Ranges]], [[Finke bioregion|Finke]], and [[Central Ranges]], and includes the [[Central Australian Mountain Ranges]] [[Centre of Plant Diversity]]. The habitats consists of thick, tough [[Triodia (plant)|spinifex]] grassland with some wooded areas of [[myall]] and [[Acacia coriacea|desert oak]] ''(Acacia coriacea)''. The region and the MacDonnell Ranges in particular are home to a number of specialised endemic plant species including the [[Livistona mariae|cabbage palm]]s of [[Palm Valley (Northern Territory)|Palm Valley]] in [[Finke Gorge National Park]].
==Fauna== Birds include the [[red-tailed black cockatoo]] and the [[spinifexbird]] while animals include the [[black-flanked rock-wallaby]] population of the MacDonnell Ranges and the [[Australian green tree frog|green tree frog]].
Overgrazing by cattle and introduced animals including horses, donkeys and rabbits are a threat to habitats.
